~☁️ Cloud Computing Principles & CAP Theorem

Cloud computing provides on-demand access to computing resources such as servers, storage, databases, networking, and software over the internet. It enables organizations to scale resources efficiently while reducing infrastructure costs.

1. CAP Theorem

The CAP Theorem, proposed by computer scientist Eric Brewer, states that a distributed system can guarantee only two out of the following three properties at the same time:

C – Consistency
A – Availability
P – Partition Tolerance

During a network partition (communication failure between nodes), a distributed system must choose between Consistency and Availability.

The Three Components of CAP
1. Consistency (C)

Consistency means every user receives the same and most recent data, regardless of which server they access.

Example:
If you transfer ₹1,000 from one bank account to another, every ATM, mobile app, and website should immediately display the updated balance.

Advantages:

Accurate data
No stale or outdated information

Disadvantage:

Users may have to wait if the system is synchronizing data.
2. Availability (A)

Availability means every request receives a response, even if some servers have failed.

The response may not always contain the latest data.

Example:
A shopping website continues to work during heavy traffic, even if some product information is slightly outdated.

Advantages:

Fast responses
High uptime

Disadvantage:

Users may temporarily see old data.
3. Partition Tolerance (P)

Partition Tolerance means the system continues operating even if communication between servers is interrupted.

Example:
If one data center loses network connectivity, another data center continues serving users.

Advantages:

High fault tolerance
System remains operational during network failures
2. CP (Consistency + Partition Tolerance)

A CP system guarantees:

Consistency
Partition Tolerance

It sacrifices Availability during a network partition.

Example

A banking system.

If two servers cannot communicate, the system may temporarily reject transactions instead of returning incorrect account balances.

Characteristics:

Strong consistency
May delay or reject requests during failures
Suitable for banking and financial applications
3. AP (Availability + Partition Tolerance)

An AP system guarantees:

Availability
Partition Tolerance

It sacrifices Consistency.

Example

A social media platform.

When you upload a photo, some users may see it immediately while others see it a few seconds later.

Characteristics:

Always responds to requests
Data becomes consistent eventually
Suitable for social media and e-commerce
4. CA (Consistency + Availability)

A CA system guarantees:

Consistency
Availability

It does not provide Partition Tolerance.

Example

A single-server database inside one office network.

Since there is no distributed network, partition issues do not occur.

Characteristics:

Consistent data
High availability
Not suitable for distributed cloud systems
CAP Theorem Summary
Type	Consistency	Availability	Partition Tolerance	Example
CP	✅	❌	✅	Banking systems
AP	❌	✅	✅	Social media, e-commerce
CA	✅	✅	❌	Single-server applications
5. Cloud Computing Principles

Cloud computing provides computing resources over the internet instead of using local servers.

Key Principles
On-demand self-service
Broad network access
Resource pooling
Rapid elasticity (scaling)
Measured service (pay-as-you-go)
Example

A company increases server capacity during a sale and reduces it afterward, paying only for the resources used.

6. Fault Tolerance

Fault Tolerance is the ability of a system to continue operating even if one or more components fail.

Instead of stopping completely, the system switches to backup resources.

Example

An online banking website uses multiple servers. If one server fails, another server immediately takes over, and customers continue using the service.

Techniques
Multiple servers
Data replication
Backup systems
Load balancing
Automatic failover
Benefits
High availability
Reduced downtime
Better user experience
7. SLA (Service Level Agreement)

An SLA (Service Level Agreement) is a contract between a service provider and a customer that defines the expected level of service.

It specifies:

Uptime guarantee
Performance targets
Response time
Support availability
Compensation for service failures
Example

A cloud provider promises 99.9% uptime.

If the uptime falls below the agreed level, the customer may receive service credits or compensation.

Common SLA Uptime Values
Uptime	Maximum Downtime per Year
99%	~3.65 days
99.9%	~8.76 hours
99.99%	~52.6 minutes
99.999%	~5.26 minutes
8. Reliability

Reliability is the ability of a system to perform its intended function correctly and consistently over time without failures.

A reliable system:

Produces accurate results
Experiences fewer failures
Recovers quickly from problems
Example

An online payment gateway processes transactions correctly 24/7 with very few errors.

Ways to Improve Reliability
Regular backups
Monitoring and alerts
Redundant servers
Preventive maintenance
Automated recovery mechanisms
Difference Between Reliability and Availability
Reliability	Availability
Ability to perform correctly without failures	Ability to remain operational and accessible
Focuses on correct operation	Focuses on uptime
Measured by failure rate	Measured by uptime percentage
